>
  <p>Heart failure is the heart's inability to pump enough blood to the organs, manifesting during exertion or at rest. It causes breathing difficulties, pulmonary oedema and can progress to terminal cardiac failure.</p>

  <p>There are two types: systolic failure, which is the inability to eject blood, and diastolic failure, which is the inability of the heart muscle to relax after contraction, characterised by cardiac stiffness preventing proper filling.</p>

  <p>Both types produce similar symptoms and are treated with medications to improve quality of life and life expectancy. The cardiologist helps patients understand medication use and monitor side effects.</p>

  <p>Chronic management relies on a multidisciplinary approach. The cardiologist monitors signs of worsening via echocardiography, adjusts treatment, or proposes alternatives such as special cardiac stimulators (ICD/CRT) to improve quality of life and prevent hospitalisations. Complex cases are followed up with university hospitals (HUG, CHUV, Inselspital).</p>
